'''Josiah Parker''' ([[11 May]] [[1751]]-[[11 March]] [[1810]]) was an [[United States|American]] politician who was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Virginia]] in the [[First United States Congress|First]] through [[Sixth United States Congress]]es.

Parker was born on 11 May 1751 in at the Macclesfield Estate in [[Isle of Wight County, Virginia]].  He became a member of the State Committee of Safety in [[1775]] and of the [[Virginia Convention]] that held sessions in March, July, and December of that year.

Upon the outbreak of the [[American Revolutionary War]], Parker enlisted in the [[US Army|Army]] and was commissioned [[major]] in the Fifth Virginia Regiment [[13 February]] [[1776]], [[lieutenant colonel]] on [[28 July]] [[1777]], and full [[colonel]] on [[1 April]] [[1778]].  He served under [[Charles Lee (general)|General Charles Lee]] in Virginia until the fall of 1776, when he was transferred to [[George Washington]]<U+2019>s army.  He resigned from the Army on [[12 July]] [[1778]] and became a member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] for 1778, [[1779]], [[1782]] and [[1783]].

Parker became a [[US Navy|naval]] officer at [[Portsmouth, Virginia]] in [[1786]] and the was an unsuccessful candidate for delegate to the Virginia Convention in [[1788]]. 

He was elected to the [[First United States Congress]], was reelected to the [[Second United States Congress|Second]] and [[Third United States Congress|Third Congresses]] and reelected as a [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] to the [[Fourth United States Congress|Fourth]] through [[Sixth United States Congress]].

After his service in the Congress, Parker engaged in agricultural pursuits and died in Macclesfield, Virginia, 11 March 1810.  He is intered in the private burial ground on his estate "Macclesfield" in Isle of Wight County, Virginia.

